ROS2¶

ROS 2 (Robot Operating System 2) is a set of software libraries and tools designed to help developers build robotic applications. It's a second-generation version of the original ROS, addressing many limitations from ROS 1 while introducing improvements in performance, security, and real-time capabilities.

Installation of ROS2:¶

In [ ]:
sudo apt update && sudo apt install curl -y
sudo curl -sSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ros/rosdistro/master/ros.asc | sudo apt-key add -
sudo sh -c 'echo "deb [trusted=yes] http://packages.ros.org/ros2/ubuntu $(lsb_release -cs) main" > /etc/apt/sources.list.d/ros2-latest.list'
In [ ]:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install ros-humble-desktop
In [ ]:
source /opt/ros/humble/setup.bash

Basics in ROS2:¶

1. ROS2 Workspace¶

A workspace in ROS 2 is a directory where you organize and build your ROS 2 projects (packages).

Create the Workspace Directory¶

First, you need to create a directory that will serve as your workspace. Inside this directory, you will create a src folder to hold your packages.

In [ ]:
mkdir -p ~/ros2_ws/src
cd ~/ros2_ws

Initialize the Workspace¶

Before building anything, you need to ensure the workspace is initialized properly. The src directory should be empty for the initial setup, but it will contain your packages later.

In [ ]:
cd ~/ros2_ws
colcon build

Source the Workspace¶

After building your workspace, you need to source it so that your environment knows about the packages in the workspace.

In [ ]:
source install/setup.bash

If you want to automatically source your workspace whenever you open a new terminal, you can add the above command to your .bashrc file:

In [ ]:
echo "source ~/ros2_ws/install/setup.bash" >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc

2.Creating a ROS 2 Package¶

ROS 2 packages contain the code, data, and other resources that make up a part of your robot system. In this section, we’ll create a new package inside the src folder of your workspace.

Navigate to the Workspace¶

Make sure you are in the workspace directory and in the src folder where the packages reside:

In [ ]:
cd ~/ros2_ws/src
Create a New Package¶

Use the ros2 pkg create command to create a new package. You can specify the name, build type, dependencies, and more.

Here’s an example command to create a package named my_package:

In [ ]:
ros2 pkg create my_package --build-type ament_cmake --dependencies rclcpp std_msgs
  1. --build-type ament_cmake: Specifies the build system (ament_cmake is for CMake-based packages).
  2. --dependencies rclcpp std_msgs: Specifies the dependencies. Here, rclcpp is the C++ client library, and std_msgs provides standard message types.
Package Structure¶
  1. CMakeLists.txt: Defines how the package is built.
  2. package.xml: Contains package metadata like name, version, dependencies, etc.
  3. src/: This is where you place your source code files.

Now Starting with simple node¶

3. Add a Simple Node in C++:¶

In [ ]:
touch ~/ros2_ws/src/my_package/src/my_node.cpp

Add this code to my_node.cpp to create a basic ROS 2 node that publishes messages:

In [ ]:
#include <chrono>
#include <rclcpp/rclcpp.hpp>
#include <std_msgs/msg/string.hpp>

using namespace std::chrono_literals;

class MyNode : public rclcpp::Node
{
public:
  MyNode() : Node("my_publisher_node")
  {
    publisher_ = this->create_publisher<std_msgs::msg::String>("topic", 10);
    timer_ = this->create_wall_timer(500ms, std::bind(&MyNode::timer_callback, this));
  }

private:
  void timer_callback()
  {
    auto message = std_msgs::msg::String();
    message.data = "Hello, ROS 2!";
    RCLCPP_INFO(this->get_logger(), "Publishing: '%s'", message.data.c_str());
    publisher_->publish(message);
  }

  rclcpp::Publisher<std_msgs::msg::String>::SharedPtr publisher_;
  rclcpp::TimerBase::SharedPtr timer_;
};

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
  rclcpp::init(argc, argv);
  rclcpp::spin(std::make_shared<MyNode>());
  rclcpp::shutdown();
  return 0;
}

Modify the CMakelists.txt¶

Modify the CMakeLists.txt to compile your C++ node:

Open CMakeLists.txt and add the following lines:

In [ ]:
find_package(rclcpp REQUIRED)
find_package(std_msgs REQUIRED)

add_executable(my_node src/my_node.cpp)

ament_target_dependencies(my_node rclcpp std_msgs)

install(TARGETS
  my_node
  DESTINATION lib/${PROJECT_NAME})

Build the Package¶

Now, return to the root of your workspace and build the package using colcon build.

In [ ]:
cd ~/ros2_ws
colcon build

Source the Workspace¶

Source your workspace again so that ROS 2 can find the new package:

In [ ]:
source install/setup.bash

Run the Node¶

Finally, you can run your new ROS 2 node using the ros2 run command:

In [ ]:
ros2 run my_package my_node

This will start the node, and you should see output in the terminal every 500ms as the node publishes messages.

4. Create a Launch File¶

Create a launch folder in your package:

In [ ]:
mkdir ~/ros2_ws/src/my_package/launch

Create a new Python-based launch file, my_launch.py, in the launch folder:

In [ ]:
touch ~/ros2_ws/src/my_package/launch/my_launch.py

Add the following content to the launch file:

In [ ]:
from launch import LaunchDescription
from launch_ros.actions import Node

def generate_launch_description():
    return LaunchDescription([
        Node(
            package='my_package',
            executable='my_node',
            output='screen'
        ),
    ])
Modify CMakeLists.txt to Include the Launch Directory:¶

To install the launch files as part of your package, you need to modify the CMakeLists.txt file to ensure the launch files are installed when you build your package.

Add the following lines to install the launch files:

In [ ]:
# Find the necessary packages
find_package(ament_cmake REQUIRED)
find_package(rclcpp REQUIRED)

# Install the launch files
install(DIRECTORY launch/
  DESTINATION share/${PROJECT_NAME}/launch
)

# Install executables (if any)
install(TARGETS
  my_node
  DESTINATION lib/${PROJECT_NAME})

# ament package macros
ament_package()

Run the Launch File¶

To run the node with the launch file:

In [ ]:
ros2 launch my_package my_launch.py

This will start the node specified in the launch file.

Check Node Execution and Logs¶

Run the node again and check if any error or warning messages appear in the terminal.

In [ ]:
ros2 run my_package my_node
Verify the Topic is Being Published¶

Use ros2 topic list to verify that the topic is being created. (In another terminal)

In [ ]:
ros2 topic list

You should see /topic in the list. If the topic doesn’t appear, there might be an issue with how the publisher is being created.

Check the Topic Message with ros2 topic echo¶

Check if messages are being published on the topic:

In [ ]:
ros2 topic echo /topic

If messages like "Hello, ROS 2!" appear in the terminal, the node is working fine, and the issue could be elsewhere (e.g., with a subscriber node or incorrect topic name in a subscriber).

Subscriber Node:¶

write a C++ subscriber node for the publisher node above:

In [ ]:
#include <rclcpp/rclcpp.hpp>
#include <std_msgs/msg/string.hpp>

class MySubscriberNode : public rclcpp::Node
{
public:
  MySubscriberNode() : Node("my_subscriber_node")
  {
    // Create a subscription on the same topic "topic" the publisher uses
    subscription_ = this->create_subscription<std_msgs::msg::String>(
        "topic", 10, std::bind(&MySubscriberNode::topic_callback, this, std::placeholders::_1));
  }

private:
  void topic_callback(const std_msgs::msg::String::SharedPtr msg) const
  {
    RCLCPP_INFO(this->get_logger(), "Received: '%s'", msg->data.c_str());
  }

  rclcpp::Subscription<std_msgs::msg::String>::SharedPtr subscription_;
};

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
  rclcpp::init(argc, argv);
  rclcpp::spin(std::make_shared<MySubscriberNode>());
  rclcpp::shutdown();
  return 0;
}

In this C++ subscriber node:

  1. Create_subscription(): Creates a subscriber that listens to the "topic" topic. When a message is received, it calls the topic_callback() function.
  2. The message is printed to the console using RCLCPP_INFO().

CMakeLists.txt Modifications for C++ Subscriber¶

If you're using C++, you will need to ensure that your CMakeLists.txt is configured to build both your publisher and subscriber nodes.

Open your CMakeLists.txt file. Add the following lines to ensure both nodes are built:

In [ ]:
# Add the publisher and subscriber executables
add_executable(my_publisher_node src/my_node.cpp)
ament_target_dependencies(my_publisher_node rclcpp std_msgs)

add_executable(my_subscriber_node src/my_sub_node.cpp)
ament_target_dependencies(my_subscriber_node rclcpp std_msgs)

# Install the executables
install(TARGETS
  my_publisher_node
  my_subscriber_node
  DESTINATION lib/${PROJECT_NAME})

Rebuild the workspace

In [ ]:
cd ~/ros2_ws
colcon build

Source the workspace

In [ ]:
source install/setup.bash

Run the publisher node

In [ ]:
ros2 run my_package my_node

Run the subcriber node

In [ ]:
ros2 run my_package my_subscriber_node

Visualizing Nodes and Topics

In [ ]:
rqt_graph

rqt_graph :¶

rqt_graph is a tool in ROS (Robot Operating System) and ROS 2 that provides a visual representation of the nodes and topics within your ROS system. It shows the relationships between nodes (which publish and subscribe to topics) and can help you visualize the flow of messages between different components of your robot or software system.
